What would the world be like without Linux?
More than twenty years ago, Linus Torvalds, the father of Linux, said, &ldquo;If 386BSD had been available before I created Linux, then Linux might not have been born.&rdquo;
Later, when people look back and reflect, there is no shortage of people who think: &ldquo;If Linux had not flourished, FreeBSD would have filled the void today.&rdquo;
BSD (Berkeley Software Distribution, also known as Berkeley Unix), the most inextricable offshoot of Unix, had its cradle at the University of California, Berkeley, the most radical leftist stronghold in the United States at the time.

